00:02:54.970 --> 00:02:57.780
And it's a story of Thomas
Edison, known to you guys

00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:59.682
probably as a really
great inventor.

00:02:59.682 --> 00:03:01.140
But what a lot of
people don't know

00:03:01.140 --> 00:03:03.810
is that Edison was an
even better businessman.

00:03:03.810 --> 00:03:06.320
He was kind of like the
Steve Jobs of his day.

00:03:06.320 --> 00:03:08.610
And what Edison was a
really, really good at

00:03:08.610 --> 00:03:12.990
was gathering a bunch of
engineers, understanding

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:15.570
what was the next
big thing that would

00:03:15.570 --> 00:03:19.110
capture people's attention
that would really wow them.

00:03:19.110 --> 00:03:21.090
And then bringing together
really smart people

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:25.610
to make those things and kind of
take all the credit after that.

00:03:25.610 --> 00:03:28.340
And so around the turn
of the 20th century,

00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:31.040
Edison came up with an
invention called a kinetoscope.

00:03:31.040 --> 00:03:34.430
And what Edison realized
was that if you took still

00:03:34.430 --> 00:03:38.420
images and moved them in rapid
succession in front of light,

00:03:38.420 --> 00:03:40.850
you could create the
illusion of life.

00:03:40.850 --> 00:03:42.680
You could create
a motion picture.

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:46.400
And whenever Edison knew
that he had a really, really

00:03:46.400 --> 00:03:49.730
good invention, he would
build up a lot of hype.

00:03:49.730 --> 00:03:53.120
Like Jobs, he would
pack a bunch of people

00:03:53.120 --> 00:03:55.520
into a large auditorium.

00:03:55.520 --> 00:03:57.800
In this case, it would
be an opera house.

00:03:57.800 --> 00:03:59.390
And people would
come out, and they

00:03:59.390 --> 00:04:03.170
would put on their best
blazers and suits and top hats,

00:04:03.170 --> 00:04:04.430
their finest furs.

00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:07.460
And they would sit in
anticipation for Edison

00:04:07.460 --> 00:04:08.600
to come out.

00:04:08.600 --> 00:04:11.310
And Edison would wait, and
he'd wait for them to build up,

00:04:11.310 --> 00:04:13.960
wait for all the anticipation
to build up, and he'd come out.

00:04:13.960 --> 00:04:17.120
I don't know if like Jobs he
would wear black turtleneck

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:19.430
and put his hands like this
in front of a spotlight,

00:04:19.430 --> 00:04:21.640
but I'd like to
imagine that he did.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:25.070
And so Edison came out and he
unveiled his newest invention

00:04:25.070 --> 00:04:26.600
of the kinetoscope.

00:04:26.600 --> 00:04:30.830
And it started to play,
and people gasped.

00:04:30.830 --> 00:04:33.800
People ran up to the screen and
put their hands in front of it.

00:04:33.800 --> 00:04:35.300
They couldn't believe
what they were

00:04:35.300 --> 00:04:37.280
seeing, that it wasn't real.

00:04:37.280 --> 00:04:39.180
And you know what they saw?

00:04:39.180 --> 00:04:40.060
It's this.

00:04:53.800 --> 00:04:54.740
It was garbage.

00:04:54.740 --> 00:04:56.120
People literally
watched garbage.

00:04:56.120 --> 00:04:59.570
This first movie was
straight-up garbage.

00:04:59.570 --> 00:05:02.750
People put on their finest
furs, their best top hats.

00:05:02.750 --> 00:05:06.370
They got a babysitter to go
and watch the kids at home

00:05:06.370 --> 00:05:08.510
so that they could
watch garbage.

00:05:08.510 --> 00:05:11.740
But the thing is they loved it.

00:05:11.740 --> 00:05:14.560
And this led to the
launch of Hollywood.

00:05:14.560 --> 00:05:18.430
There's 23 movies released
between 1900 and 1909;

00:05:18.430 --> 00:05:21.040
the next decade, over 4,600.

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:24.220
In the '20s, nearly 7,000
films, and some of those

00:05:24.220 --> 00:05:26.200
films were quite good.

00:05:26.200 --> 00:05:27.700
They were hits.

00:05:27.700 --> 00:05:29.686
But then something happened.

00:05:29.686 --> 00:05:31.810
And the number of films
being produced in Hollywood

00:05:31.810 --> 00:05:33.490
started to decline.

00:05:33.490 --> 00:05:34.740
And there's a reason for that.

00:05:34.740 --> 00:05:37.770
It's that while there's a few
really good films, most of them

00:05:37.770 --> 00:05:38.340
were garbage.

00:05:38.340 --> 00:05:41.060
Most of them had no narrative,
no plot, and no story.

00:05:41.060 --> 00:05:44.809
They were just grainy footage
of a train or garbage.

00:05:44.809 --> 00:05:47.100
And it's actually one of the
first storytelling lessons

00:05:47.100 --> 00:05:50.790
that we'll learn, which is
that garbage stories are

00:05:50.790 --> 00:05:53.070
only cool when
there's they're novel.

00:05:53.070 --> 00:05:54.660
Only when that medium
first comes out

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:57.900
were people willing to
come in and get dressed up

00:05:57.900 --> 00:06:00.120
all fancy to go watch garbage.

00:06:00.120 --> 00:06:01.860
But once it stopped
being new, they

00:06:01.860 --> 00:06:04.090
stopped wanting to
keep coming out.

00:06:04.090 --> 00:06:08.040
And this is a pattern that we
actually see with all mediums,

00:06:08.040 --> 00:06:09.250
with web content.

00:06:09.250 --> 00:06:11.340
So I don't know about you
guys, but when I first

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:14.340
got the internet, I
got that AOL dial-up,

00:06:14.340 --> 00:06:17.040
had that sweet serenade of
shutting off my mom's phone

00:06:17.040 --> 00:06:18.840
line and dialing up.

00:06:18.840 --> 00:06:20.580
GeoCities was my jam.

00:06:20.580 --> 00:06:23.640
I was just enamored,
from a young age,

00:06:23.640 --> 00:06:26.280
with this dynamic where
you could go and see

00:06:26.280 --> 00:06:28.680
this information and
content that people from all

00:06:28.680 --> 00:06:30.659
over the world were
posting, or see stuff

00:06:30.659 --> 00:06:31.950
that your friends were posting.

00:06:31.950 --> 00:06:33.741
And it didn't matter
if it was good or not.

00:06:33.741 --> 00:06:36.810
I'd spent hours reading
random Xangas and LiveJournals

00:06:36.810 --> 00:06:39.010
and GeoCities pages.

00:06:39.010 --> 00:06:43.096
I would read the embarrassing
emo poems and confessionals

00:06:43.096 --> 00:06:44.220
that my friends would post.

00:06:44.220 --> 00:06:47.130
And I have to admit, I probably
posted some of those myself

00:06:47.130 --> 00:06:48.030
as well.

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:50.110
Please, no one
try and find them.

00:06:50.110 --> 00:06:52.200
I'm sure they exist somewhere.

00:06:52.200 --> 00:06:54.820
But eventually what
we get is that that

00:06:54.820 --> 00:06:55.920
stopped becoming novel.

00:06:55.920 --> 00:06:59.100
And before long,
the internet became

00:06:59.100 --> 00:07:02.340
this kind of cesspool
of garbage content being

00:07:02.340 --> 00:07:05.060
posted onto the web.

00:07:05.060 --> 00:07:10.500
We got bad eHow articles about
how to write bad eHow articles.

00:07:10.500 --> 00:07:12.810
We saw this with blogs.

00:07:12.810 --> 00:07:14.310
When the first-person
blog came out,

00:07:14.310 --> 00:07:16.380
we had people like Bill
Simmons and Pete Cashmore

00:07:16.380 --> 00:07:18.780
that were able to build this
giant audience without a lot

00:07:18.780 --> 00:07:22.920
of promotion just by posting
these first-person blog

00:07:22.920 --> 00:07:26.670
posts and essays and online.

00:07:26.670 --> 00:07:28.980
But eventually, we just got
more and more of that crap.

00:07:28.980 --> 00:07:33.105
We got this slew, this
cesspool of first-person blogs

00:07:33.105 --> 00:07:33.730
and narratives.

00:07:33.730 --> 00:07:36.070
It became harder and
harder to break through.

00:07:36.070 --> 00:07:37.730
We saw this with infographics.

00:07:37.730 --> 00:07:39.229
It used to be that
if you could make

00:07:39.229 --> 00:07:41.520
an infographics in
the early 2000s,

00:07:41.520 --> 00:07:43.260
you'd get on, like,
any blog out there.

00:07:43.260 --> 00:07:46.160
But so many people started
creating bad infographics that

00:07:46.160 --> 00:07:49.110
didn't communicate
information very well,

00:07:49.110 --> 00:07:52.320
that didn't tell a story,
that by 2008, Mashable

00:07:52.320 --> 00:07:55.290
was banning any guest post
submissions or any submissions

00:07:55.290 --> 00:07:56.820
with infographics in them.

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:58.410
We saw this with Facebook.

00:07:58.410 --> 00:08:00.870
So when brands
first got Facebook,

00:08:00.870 --> 00:08:02.880
when first Facebook
first opened to brands,

00:08:02.880 --> 00:08:04.620
it seemed like a miracle.

00:08:04.620 --> 00:08:06.510
You could just
post, like this post

00:08:06.510 --> 00:08:09.990
if you will if you hate
Mondays, and people would get

00:08:09.990 --> 00:08:11.970
hundreds and hundreds of likes.

00:08:11.970 --> 00:08:16.880
Brands would get a each to
30%, 40% of their audience.

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:20.500
But what happened is brands
kept posting that kind of crap.

00:08:20.500 --> 00:08:22.776
And eventually people
stopped engaging with them.

00:08:22.776 --> 00:08:23.400
It wasn't cool.

00:08:23.400 --> 00:08:25.080
It wasn't novel
anymore that you can

00:08:25.080 --> 00:08:27.750
interact with Tide on Facebook.

00:08:27.750 --> 00:08:30.250
And reach dropped
to less than 2%.

00:08:30.250 --> 00:08:33.940
We saw this with Instagram,
with Pinterest, with LinkedIn.

00:08:33.940 --> 00:08:36.480
The same pattern is
that eventually there's

00:08:36.480 --> 00:08:38.730
new platforms, people
are interested in it,

00:08:38.730 --> 00:08:41.970
and it gets flooded
with so much garbage.

00:08:41.970 --> 00:08:44.910
And this is what we
call the Edison cycle.

00:08:44.910 --> 00:08:47.350
Technology enables a new medium.

00:08:47.350 --> 00:08:49.240
People make garbage.

00:08:49.240 --> 00:08:51.770
And then people
ignore the garbage.

00:08:51.770 --> 00:08:56.200
So in conclusion,
everything is garbage.

00:08:56.200 --> 00:08:57.926
That's the end of my talk.

