00:10:26.380 --> 00:10:29.660
In any medium, we'll
see that the key

00:10:29.660 --> 00:10:32.720
is that creativity and great
stories need to break through.

00:10:32.720 --> 00:10:36.200
And this led to the
advent of blockbusters.

00:10:36.200 --> 00:10:39.560
And it's something that we
saw revitalize the industry,

00:10:39.560 --> 00:10:42.650
as people started putting in the
care and effort and investment

00:10:42.650 --> 00:10:44.900
to make better and better films.

00:10:44.900 --> 00:10:46.640
And we see this
with all mediums.

00:10:46.640 --> 00:10:50.510
So let's go back to web
content, by the late 2000s,

00:10:50.510 --> 00:10:56.370
content on the web had a lot
of noise, a lot of mess in it.

00:10:56.370 --> 00:11:00.060
And especially in financial
content, so banks,

00:11:00.060 --> 00:11:03.080
financial brands had started
posting content on the web.

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:07.210
But most of it was these bad
PDFs, white papers, basically

00:11:07.210 --> 00:11:10.270
bank brochures
re-posted to the web.

00:11:10.270 --> 00:11:13.200
Then there is one company
called Mint that came along.

00:11:13.200 --> 00:11:14.700
That was one of our
first customers.

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:17.817
And I think when we think
about brands creating content

00:11:17.817 --> 00:11:20.150
on the web, it's a really
inspiring example because they

00:11:20.150 --> 00:11:23.420
thought, what if we
talked about the one thing

00:11:23.420 --> 00:11:25.890
that everyone
really cares about,

00:11:25.890 --> 00:11:28.580
which is how to manage
your money better?

00:11:28.580 --> 00:11:31.850
Whether you need to buy a
house, pay student loans,

00:11:31.850 --> 00:11:33.940
just save, better manage
your credit card debt,

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:35.580
it's something that
matters to anyone.

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:39.920
They found that no one was
doing a very good job of talking

00:11:39.920 --> 00:11:41.390
about money on the web.

00:11:41.390 --> 00:11:44.810
So they started writing in
very colloquial language,

00:11:44.810 --> 00:11:47.540
first person, very
visual-heavy language.

00:11:47.540 --> 00:11:50.120
And they started amassing
millions of readers.

00:11:50.120 --> 00:11:51.770
They put out things
like a visual guide

00:11:51.770 --> 00:11:55.790
to the financial crisis, that
are reported all over the web.

00:11:55.790 --> 00:11:57.290
And they're one of
our first clients

00:11:57.290 --> 00:12:01.830
that really showed us how
brands and businesses that

00:12:01.830 --> 00:12:04.500
told really good dynamic
stories could build

00:12:04.500 --> 00:12:06.450
incredible relationships,
because people

00:12:06.450 --> 00:12:09.556
were emailing Mint every day.

00:12:09.556 --> 00:12:11.430
Thousands of people
would email Mint and say,

00:12:11.430 --> 00:12:15.000
thank you for helping me
pay down my student debt

00:12:15.000 --> 00:12:17.250
or pay off my car
or buy a house,

00:12:17.250 --> 00:12:19.720
because they were making a
difference in people's lives

00:12:19.720 --> 00:12:22.490
through the stories
they were telling.

00:12:22.490 --> 00:12:24.560
And this is
something that we see

00:12:24.560 --> 00:12:27.020
is that the science
of storytelling

00:12:27.020 --> 00:12:30.470
actually shows that great
stories build relationships.

00:12:30.470 --> 00:12:32.120
Great stories make us care.

00:12:32.120 --> 00:12:34.640
Over the last 10 years,
a lot of new research

00:12:34.640 --> 00:12:37.250
has come out that shows
that a strong connection

00:12:37.250 --> 00:12:41.450
between storytelling and the
chemical oxytocin in our brain.

00:12:41.450 --> 00:12:43.820
For a while, we didn't
know much about oxytocin.

00:12:43.820 --> 00:12:46.430
We just knew it was something
that was released when mothers

00:12:46.430 --> 00:12:48.830
would be close to their babies.

00:12:48.830 --> 00:12:52.610
But what we have seen
of late is research

00:12:52.610 --> 00:12:55.550
that shows that when we
engage with really, really

00:12:55.550 --> 00:12:58.340
good stories, when we are
captivated by a story,

00:12:58.340 --> 00:13:00.950
it actually releases
this empathy drug

00:13:00.950 --> 00:13:04.280
oxytocin in our minds
that makes us care more

00:13:04.280 --> 00:13:06.315
about the person that's
telling us the story,

00:13:06.315 --> 00:13:08.690
be it the protagonist, the
brand that's telling it to us.

00:13:08.690 --> 00:13:12.710
It builds a connection between
us and the person telling it.

00:13:12.710 --> 00:13:15.620
And research has shown that
storytelling can break down

00:13:15.620 --> 00:13:17.720
barriers to foster
compassion, tolerance,

00:13:17.720 --> 00:13:19.580
and respect for differences.

00:13:19.580 --> 00:13:22.190
It's shown that it can
build those interpersonal

00:13:22.190 --> 00:13:25.020
relationships and that
sense of connectedness.

00:13:25.020 --> 00:13:27.200
So we think about
this modern world,

00:13:27.200 --> 00:13:32.180
where that barrier between
businesses and individuals

00:13:32.180 --> 00:13:34.390
and the rest of the world
has been broken down,

00:13:34.390 --> 00:13:36.860
where we no longer have
a means of just having

00:13:36.860 --> 00:13:38.360
someone's captivated intention.

00:13:38.360 --> 00:13:40.550
But we have to earn
it every second

00:13:40.550 --> 00:13:43.460
because we have this magical
device buzzing in our pocket,

00:13:43.460 --> 00:13:47.390
beckoning us for our attention
and with thousands of stories,

00:13:47.390 --> 00:13:49.520
that you need a really
compelling narrative

00:13:49.520 --> 00:13:53.160
to build those relationships
with people and make them care.

00:13:53.160 --> 00:13:55.310
And as human beings,
we are absolutely

00:13:55.310 --> 00:13:56.900
programmed for stories.

00:13:56.900 --> 00:13:59.310
When we hear a story,
the neurons in our brains

00:13:59.310 --> 00:14:01.130
fire at five times
that capacity.

00:14:01.130 --> 00:14:03.200
It illuminates the
city of our mind.

00:14:03.200 --> 00:14:06.470
And we store information
so much better.

00:14:06.470 --> 00:14:09.680
And that's what's led to the
rise of this thing called

00:14:09.680 --> 00:14:11.360
content marketing,
which is essentially

00:14:11.360 --> 00:14:14.120
the practice of a
brand telling its story

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:17.180
to engage with people, to build
relationships with the folks

00:14:17.180 --> 00:14:19.040
that it wants to sell to.

00:14:19.040 --> 00:14:21.560
But this doesn't have
just to do with marketing.

00:14:21.560 --> 00:14:23.570
It has to do with
all the relationships

00:14:23.570 --> 00:14:26.390
that we have as human beings,
with the relationships that we

00:14:26.390 --> 00:14:29.030
have as a leader with the
people in our company,

00:14:29.030 --> 00:14:31.190
as a team member with the
other people on our team.

00:14:31.190 --> 00:14:34.370
So when we tell our story,
we're able to draw people

00:14:34.370 --> 00:14:39.470
in and build empathy
between us and them.

00:14:39.470 --> 00:14:42.800
And we really believe that
the businesses of the future

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:45.050
will figure out how to
tell breakthrough stories,

00:14:45.050 --> 00:14:47.050
or they're going to fail,
because there's really

00:14:47.050 --> 00:14:49.490
no other option if you
want to actually gain

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:52.950
people's attention and
a place in their minds.

00:14:52.950 --> 00:14:55.180
And so we think about
the three keys that

00:14:55.180 --> 00:14:59.470
will lead to great storytelling
by businesses and leaders

00:14:59.470 --> 00:15:01.060
and everyone else in the future.

00:15:01.060 --> 00:15:02.710
Telling those
breakthrough stories

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:05.440
that goes above and
beyond just the garbage

00:15:05.440 --> 00:15:07.900
status quo of a
given medium is key.

00:15:07.900 --> 00:15:10.030
But there are other things
as well that we think

00:15:10.030 --> 00:15:12.490
will have a really big impact.

00:15:12.490 --> 00:15:15.470
Next story I want to
tell is of Netflix.

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:18.980
So in 2008, Netflix acquired
the rights to "House of Cards."

00:15:18.980 --> 00:15:20.980
Everyone thought they
were crazy at the time

00:15:20.980 --> 00:15:24.670
because everyone said, Netflix,
you're a technology company.

00:15:24.670 --> 00:15:26.530
Why are you spending
$100 million on a show?

00:15:26.530 --> 00:15:28.750
But "House of Cards"
was a really big hit.

00:15:28.750 --> 00:15:30.830
Next they came out with
"Arrested Development."

00:15:30.830 --> 00:15:32.624
Everyone was like,
OK, that makes sense.

00:15:32.624 --> 00:15:34.540
"Arrested Development"
was a big cult classic.

00:15:34.540 --> 00:15:35.650
People loved it.

00:15:35.650 --> 00:15:37.126
But then they came
out with a show

00:15:37.126 --> 00:15:38.500
called "Orange is
the New Black,"

00:15:38.500 --> 00:15:41.290
and people started to scratch
their heads because there

00:15:41.290 --> 00:15:43.870
was no one famous in
"Orange is the New Black."

00:15:43.870 --> 00:15:47.110
There is no
Kevin-Spacey-type figure,

00:15:47.110 --> 00:15:51.040
who obviously wouldn't do so
well today, but at the time,

00:15:51.040 --> 00:15:53.530
was extremely popular, in
"Orange is the New Black."

00:15:53.530 --> 00:15:57.480
In fact, the biggest star in
"Orange is the New Black,"

00:15:57.480 --> 00:16:01.210
the biggest name, was this guy.

00:16:01.210 --> 00:16:03.910
And no one was actually going
to go start watching a show

00:16:03.910 --> 00:16:05.440
to see this guy.

00:16:05.440 --> 00:16:07.390
But the thing that
Netflix knew--

00:16:07.390 --> 00:16:10.645
I'm just going to leave
this up for a second.

00:16:10.645 --> 00:16:16.690
The thing that Netflix
knew is that they

00:16:16.690 --> 00:16:22.030
had so much data about their
audience's viewing habits.

00:16:22.030 --> 00:16:24.887
So Netflix is
obsessed with data,

00:16:24.887 --> 00:16:27.490
with tracking how
people watch things,

00:16:27.490 --> 00:16:30.460
the succession in which
they'll watch shows,

00:16:30.460 --> 00:16:33.430
their finish rate on shows,
their re-watch rate on shows,

00:16:33.430 --> 00:16:36.040
and the interlap
between when people

00:16:36.040 --> 00:16:37.300
watch one show or another.

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:39.850
Where is there a
correlation between watching

00:16:39.850 --> 00:16:41.500
x-show and y-show?

00:16:41.500 --> 00:16:43.961
How do people discover
shows within Netflix?

00:16:43.961 --> 00:16:45.460
What are the things
that will prompt

00:16:45.460 --> 00:16:47.230
them to start
watching a new show

00:16:47.230 --> 00:16:50.180
and then keep
watching that show?

00:16:50.180 --> 00:16:52.600
With "Orange is the
New Black," Netflix

00:16:52.600 --> 00:16:54.890
needs something pretty unique.

00:16:54.890 --> 00:16:57.070
So through all their
data, they knew

00:16:57.070 --> 00:17:00.910
that certain viewers really
loved any shows or movies

00:17:00.910 --> 00:17:03.520
with women-led ensembles.

00:17:03.520 --> 00:17:06.010
And they knew there was a big
overlap between those viewers

00:17:06.010 --> 00:17:07.450
and people who watch "Weeds."

00:17:07.450 --> 00:17:10.839
"Weeds" was one of the most
popular shows on Netflix,

00:17:10.839 --> 00:17:13.599
one of the best gets they'd ever
gotten when they licensed it

00:17:13.599 --> 00:17:14.890
from Showtime.

00:17:14.890 --> 00:17:17.530
It was constantly in the
most popular in Netflix.

00:17:17.530 --> 00:17:20.589
They saw people watching
it all the way through,

00:17:20.589 --> 00:17:23.190
calling out for work for
12 hours on a Tuesday

00:17:23.190 --> 00:17:24.829
to just sit back
and watch "Weeds"

00:17:24.829 --> 00:17:27.109
and maybe smoke up
a little themselves.

00:17:27.109 --> 00:17:30.820
And they also knew
that those people

00:17:30.820 --> 00:17:35.110
were very likely to
watch a show that was

00:17:35.110 --> 00:17:36.320
prompted to them by Netflix.

00:17:36.320 --> 00:17:37.780
So there are
certain viewers that

00:17:37.780 --> 00:17:40.750
took Netflix flicks
recommendations very seriously

00:17:40.750 --> 00:17:42.207
and would watch a
show unprompted.

00:17:42.207 --> 00:17:44.290
So they saw there's this
intersection with "Orange

00:17:44.290 --> 00:17:47.260
is the New Black," which
a women-led ensemble, that

00:17:47.260 --> 00:17:51.790
was started by the same show
runner, Jenji Kohan, as "Weeds"

00:17:51.790 --> 00:17:54.880
and would succeed
well with viewers

00:17:54.880 --> 00:17:56.920
that were prompted by
Netflix recommendations

00:17:56.920 --> 00:17:58.180
to watch this show.

00:17:58.180 --> 00:18:00.890
So they pushed it out to that
target audience of people,

00:18:00.890 --> 00:18:02.330
and they were able
to get "Orange

00:18:02.330 --> 00:18:06.280
is the New Black" to essentially
go viral with these viewers.

00:18:06.280 --> 00:18:08.920
People just watched it
all the way through.

00:18:08.920 --> 00:18:10.870
They posted on Facebook,
on Twitter about it.

00:18:10.870 --> 00:18:12.370
And "Orange is the
New Black," which

00:18:12.370 --> 00:18:14.710
was a much smaller investment
than "House of Cards"

00:18:14.710 --> 00:18:18.070
was, was a huge success
and actually paid off

00:18:18.070 --> 00:18:23.800
in three months, helping Netflix
earn over 630,000 subscribers,

00:18:23.800 --> 00:18:26.830
more than "House of Cards"
or "Arrested Development"

00:18:26.830 --> 00:18:27.970
had for them.

00:18:27.970 --> 00:18:30.190
And this is a
formula that Netflix

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:32.860
has repeated over and over,
with "Stranger Things,"

00:18:32.860 --> 00:18:35.320
with "13 Reasons Why."

00:18:35.320 --> 00:18:38.470
And while 35% of
network shows get

00:18:38.470 --> 00:18:41.770
renewed after the first
season, 70% of Netflix

00:18:41.770 --> 00:18:44.530
shows get renewed, and
that's because this data

00:18:44.530 --> 00:18:47.470
and technology power that
Netflix has gives them

00:18:47.470 --> 00:18:49.120
double the advantage.

00:18:49.120 --> 00:18:52.840
And so we think about the
future of brand storytelling,

00:18:52.840 --> 00:18:54.640
of content marketing.

00:18:54.640 --> 00:18:57.885
I truly believe that human
creativity will always be key.

00:18:57.885 --> 00:18:59.260
I think robot
writers are getting

00:18:59.260 --> 00:19:02.350
really good at doing
things like writing up

00:19:02.350 --> 00:19:04.780
game recaps from basketball
games or baseball

00:19:04.780 --> 00:19:06.490
games or any financial reports.

00:19:06.490 --> 00:19:09.430
But when it comes to
telling human stories,

00:19:09.430 --> 00:19:12.130
I think that humans will
always win in that capacity

00:19:12.130 --> 00:19:14.650
because we're able
to tell our story,

00:19:14.650 --> 00:19:17.470
and we're able to use that to
connect with people in a way

00:19:17.470 --> 00:19:18.940
that robots or AI can't.

00:19:18.940 --> 00:19:21.850
So I think that will always
be a constant in storytelling

00:19:21.850 --> 00:19:24.190
and the quality of brand
storytelling out there.

00:19:24.190 --> 00:19:27.010
But I do believe that
technology has the capacity

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:30.005
to help us really understand
what the people we want to each

00:19:30.005 --> 00:19:32.380
want to see, what's going to
engage them the most, what's

00:19:32.380 --> 00:19:34.450
going to make them call
off of work all day

00:19:34.450 --> 00:19:37.630
and sit down and
watch what we put out

00:19:37.630 --> 00:19:40.270
or read the articles
we put out, or engage

00:19:40.270 --> 00:19:43.920
with what we post out on Twitter
and Facebook and LinkedIn?

00:19:43.920 --> 00:19:45.420
And while right
now what we see is

00:19:45.420 --> 00:19:47.220
that most people in
the industry are just

00:19:47.220 --> 00:19:49.860
using a little bit of technology
to help them figure out

00:19:49.860 --> 00:19:51.420
what their audience
actually wants,

00:19:51.420 --> 00:19:52.500
what they'll engage with.

00:19:52.500 --> 00:19:54.480
The smartest people
in the industry

00:19:54.480 --> 00:19:57.750
are using the first-party
data they have available,

00:19:57.750 --> 00:20:01.260
the amazing slew of search
and social tools that we

00:20:01.260 --> 00:20:04.140
have available, many of
them put out by Google,

00:20:04.140 --> 00:20:06.720
to understand what our
audience really wants.

00:20:06.720 --> 00:20:08.820
And they're riding the
crest of that wave.

00:20:08.820 --> 00:20:11.070
And that's why I really
believe the second key will

00:20:11.070 --> 00:20:14.070
be taking advantage of
that technology advantage

00:20:14.070 --> 00:20:16.430
to tell great stories.

00:20:16.430 --> 00:20:18.590
And for my third
and final key, I

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:21.074
want to tell the story
of a young Kevin Costner.

00:20:21.074 --> 00:20:21.740
He's in a field.

00:20:21.740 --> 00:20:25.740
He's kind of looking
confused and sultry.

00:20:25.740 --> 00:20:30.100
And he hears a voice, if you
build it, they will come.

00:20:30.100 --> 00:20:31.390
And they did come.

00:20:31.390 --> 00:20:34.060
But there's one problem.

00:20:34.060 --> 00:20:35.110
They were ghosts.

00:20:35.110 --> 00:20:38.020
And so what does this have
to do with content marketing

00:20:38.020 --> 00:20:39.530
and brand storytelling?

00:20:39.530 --> 00:20:43.580
Well, right now we have
seen that [INAUDIBLE]

00:20:43.580 --> 00:20:46.700
last year's show that 5% of
all branded content put out

00:20:46.700 --> 00:20:49.370
gets 90% of the attention.

00:20:49.370 --> 00:20:51.800
And so essentially,
a lot of brands

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:54.720
are creating content, but
very few are being successful.

00:20:54.720 --> 00:20:58.180
And that's because so many
folks see creating content

00:20:58.180 --> 00:20:59.390
as the ultimate goal.

00:20:59.390 --> 00:21:01.130
They create a blog.

00:21:01.130 --> 00:21:01.997
They create content.

00:21:01.997 --> 00:21:03.080
They publish that content.

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:05.330
And they just expect
people to magically come.

00:21:05.330 --> 00:21:07.250
They expect it to work.

00:21:07.250 --> 00:21:08.720
But usually, they don't.

00:21:08.720 --> 00:21:13.820
And if they do, it might just
be some bots or some ghosts.

00:21:13.820 --> 00:21:17.870
And while content spend across
the marketing industry is up,

00:21:17.870 --> 00:21:19.070
content strategy is flat.

00:21:19.070 --> 00:21:22.550
Less than 40% of marketers
in B to B and B to C

00:21:22.550 --> 00:21:24.170
have a documented
content strategy.

00:21:24.170 --> 00:21:25.635
It's self-sabotage.

00:21:25.635 --> 00:21:27.260
And this is something
that we're really

00:21:27.260 --> 00:21:30.290
obsessed with at Contently
is creating and implementing

00:21:30.290 --> 00:21:32.600
a methodology and
a content strategy

00:21:32.600 --> 00:21:35.300
for every single client
that we work with.

00:21:35.300 --> 00:21:38.480
And we actually think there's
a simple formula for building

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:42.080
an audience that can help
marketers and brands really

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:45.821
understand the cycle of
content creation and content

00:21:45.821 --> 00:21:47.570
optimization that they
need to go through.

00:21:47.570 --> 00:21:51.830
And to explain that, I want to
go back to the 16th century,

00:21:51.830 --> 00:21:56.640
to 1500 AD, to the
advent of mass media.

00:21:56.640 --> 00:21:58.210
So during the
Italian Renaissance,

00:21:58.210 --> 00:22:02.720
it was a flourishing time
of culture, information.

00:22:02.720 --> 00:22:08.704
And there was the first
mass media publication.

00:22:08.704 --> 00:22:10.370
It was called the
[? "Ivicci." ?] It was

00:22:10.370 --> 00:22:12.770
essentially the TMZ of its day.

00:22:12.770 --> 00:22:16.670
And so what would happen is
you would have these gossip

00:22:16.670 --> 00:22:19.040
writers, and they would
go out to the churches,

00:22:19.040 --> 00:22:23.330
to the markets, and they
would gather the day's gossip.

00:22:23.330 --> 00:22:26.280
And they would come back,
and they would print it

00:22:26.280 --> 00:22:28.660
up using the printing press.

00:22:28.660 --> 00:22:30.990
It was a new invention
that came out in the time.

00:22:30.990 --> 00:22:34.970
And so they would
painstakingly go and print up

00:22:34.970 --> 00:22:38.420
these newsletters of the day,
these gossip newsletters using

00:22:38.420 --> 00:22:40.435
the printing press.

00:22:40.435 --> 00:22:41.810
And then they'd
go out and they'd

00:22:41.810 --> 00:22:44.495
distribute it all around town.

00:22:44.495 --> 00:22:45.870
But there's
something interesting

00:22:45.870 --> 00:22:46.830
that started happening.

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:48.560
So there's the [? "Ivicci" ?]
writers using the printing

00:22:48.560 --> 00:22:49.204
press.

00:22:49.204 --> 00:22:50.620
Then some other
writers said, hey,

00:22:50.620 --> 00:22:52.730
I bet we can beat
the printing press

00:22:52.730 --> 00:22:57.140
people to market if we just hand
write our gossip newsletters.

00:22:57.140 --> 00:23:00.380
So they started hand writing
the gossip newsletters.

00:23:00.380 --> 00:23:02.150
But then something happened.

00:23:02.150 --> 00:23:04.190
They started getting
their heads chopped off.

00:23:04.190 --> 00:23:06.170
Because it turned
out that people

00:23:06.170 --> 00:23:08.840
really didn't like it when you
talked about who is bribing who

00:23:08.840 --> 00:23:10.820
and who was sleeping with who.

00:23:10.820 --> 00:23:13.100
There was a lot of
gossip writers getting

00:23:13.100 --> 00:23:14.540
their heads chopped off.

00:23:14.540 --> 00:23:17.702
So big reason for that is
they'd put their name on it.

00:23:17.702 --> 00:23:20.850
It would be "The Daily
Gossip" by Antonio.

00:23:20.850 --> 00:23:22.820
So what they did
instead, started

00:23:22.820 --> 00:23:24.140
taking their name off it.

00:23:24.140 --> 00:23:26.140
And the people who were
doing the printing press

00:23:26.140 --> 00:23:27.920
started hand writing
as well because they

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:29.720
realized it was faster.

00:23:29.720 --> 00:23:31.790
And the gossip
newsletter started

00:23:31.790 --> 00:23:33.359
to flourish because
they'd go out,

00:23:33.359 --> 00:23:34.900
and they'd do it in
the dead of night

00:23:34.900 --> 00:23:36.774
so they wouldn't get
their heads chopped off.

00:23:36.774 --> 00:23:38.910
No one knew they were
posting it there.

00:23:38.910 --> 00:23:41.799
And this tells us one thing,
which is that strategy matters.

00:23:41.799 --> 00:23:44.090
How you publish it is as
important as what you publish.

00:23:44.090 --> 00:23:46.754
Just because there's a
new way of doing things,

00:23:46.754 --> 00:23:48.920
a new technology that allow
you to put it out there,

00:23:48.920 --> 00:23:51.320
doesn't mean it's
necessarily going to succeed.

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:53.420
And it's a deeper
pattern that we actually

00:23:53.420 --> 00:23:55.340
see throughout
all forms of media

00:23:55.340 --> 00:23:57.980
that have succeed throughout
time when folks are trying

00:23:57.980 --> 00:24:00.740
to build an audience,
which is that you go out,

00:24:00.740 --> 00:24:02.842
and you start creating content.

00:24:02.842 --> 00:24:04.800
You have a hypothesis
for what's going to work.

00:24:04.800 --> 00:24:06.950
So let's print out
some gossip newsletters

00:24:06.950 --> 00:24:08.600
using the printing press.

00:24:08.600 --> 00:24:10.340
Then let's engage people.

00:24:10.340 --> 00:24:13.790
Let's go out, distribute
it around town in daylight,

00:24:13.790 --> 00:24:14.540
and then optimize.

00:24:14.540 --> 00:24:15.706
So what did they figure out?

00:24:15.706 --> 00:24:17.340
It was too slow.

00:24:17.340 --> 00:24:20.950
So next, try hand writing
it, put your name on it,

00:24:20.950 --> 00:24:24.660
engage, go out, post it
around town, and optimize.

00:24:24.660 --> 00:24:27.765
Oh, shit, we're getting
our heads chopped off.

00:24:27.765 --> 00:24:29.140
So what did they
figure out next?

00:24:29.140 --> 00:24:31.780
Take the name off
it, engage, go out

00:24:31.780 --> 00:24:34.469
and distribute it in the
dead of night, then optimize.

00:24:34.469 --> 00:24:35.260
You keep your head.

00:24:35.260 --> 00:24:36.070
Everyone's happy.

00:24:36.070 --> 00:24:39.240
You have a successful
newsletter.

00:24:39.240 --> 00:24:41.020
To illustrate how this
has happened again

00:24:41.020 --> 00:24:47.440
throughout history, I want to go
to 1851, my hometown, New York,

00:24:47.440 --> 00:24:49.270
the Lower East Side.

00:24:49.270 --> 00:24:53.080
And this was the start
of, the advent of,

00:24:53.080 --> 00:24:56.230
the big mass-market newspaper.

00:24:56.230 --> 00:24:59.950
Everyone who is anyone,
anyone who was anyone

00:24:59.950 --> 00:25:01.340
had a newspaper at this point.

00:25:01.340 --> 00:25:05.740
And there was essentially two
big rivals in the newspaper

00:25:05.740 --> 00:25:07.540
market at the time in New York.

00:25:07.540 --> 00:25:10.810
There is Joseph Pulitzer
of the "New York World"

00:25:10.810 --> 00:25:13.750
and Andrew Hearst of
the "New York Journal."

00:25:13.750 --> 00:25:17.680
And at this time, the printing
press had gotten pretty good.

00:25:17.680 --> 00:25:20.824
It was a really efficient, good
piece of technology to use.

00:25:20.824 --> 00:25:22.240
You couldn't beat
someone to print

00:25:22.240 --> 00:25:23.809
by hand writing a newspaper.

00:25:23.809 --> 00:25:24.850
Printing press was great.

00:25:24.850 --> 00:25:26.350
So reporters would go out.

00:25:26.350 --> 00:25:29.890
They'd gather today's news,
bring it back, print it up

00:25:29.890 --> 00:25:31.170
in the newspaper.

00:25:31.170 --> 00:25:33.940
And then they would give
it to these chain-smoking

00:25:33.940 --> 00:25:37.765
11-year-olds to go out and
hand out to people as they

00:25:37.765 --> 00:25:38.890
were getting on the subway.

00:25:38.890 --> 00:25:40.999
They'd gawk, extra,
extra, read about it.

00:25:40.999 --> 00:25:42.790
And what they found is
because the only way

00:25:42.790 --> 00:25:45.880
to really get to sell newspapers
and get in people's hands

00:25:45.880 --> 00:25:48.520
was to have as sensational
headlines as possible,

00:25:48.520 --> 00:25:50.530
something you'll
probably find familiar

00:25:50.530 --> 00:25:52.300
if you've been on
Facebook lately.

00:25:52.300 --> 00:25:55.510
So it'd be things like, "Woman
Survives Mad Leap" and "War

00:25:55.510 --> 00:25:57.610
is Coming."

00:25:57.610 --> 00:26:00.880
But then this journalist, one
of my favorite people in history

00:26:00.880 --> 00:26:07.120
came along and proposed a better
way to tell these stories.

00:26:07.120 --> 00:26:10.000
Because at the time,
what the "New York World"

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:12.700
and "New York Journal" really
wanted was loyal subscribers.

00:26:12.700 --> 00:26:14.530
They want people who would
get the newspaper delivered

00:26:14.530 --> 00:26:16.960
to their house every day, have
a sustained model, instead

00:26:16.960 --> 00:26:19.690
of having to go and
compete for sales just

00:26:19.690 --> 00:26:22.780
by having chain-smoking
11-year-olds hawking newspapers

00:26:22.780 --> 00:26:23.710
at subway stations.

00:26:23.710 --> 00:26:26.900
And Nellie Bly was
a young journalist.

00:26:26.900 --> 00:26:29.140
She came in to Joseph
Pulitzer's office.

00:26:29.140 --> 00:26:31.270
And she asked for
a job that was seen

00:26:31.270 --> 00:26:33.340
by most as only a job
for men at the time.

00:26:33.340 --> 00:26:36.520
But she was a brilliant
woman, incredibly courageous.

00:26:36.520 --> 00:26:38.890
And what she
proposes is that she

00:26:38.890 --> 00:26:43.210
wanted to get locked up in a
mental hospital for two weeks

00:26:43.210 --> 00:26:46.300
and document everything
that was happening inside.

00:26:46.300 --> 00:26:48.730
And so Joseph Pulitzer said OK.

00:26:48.730 --> 00:26:49.240
She went.

00:26:49.240 --> 00:26:50.580
She got locked up.

00:26:50.580 --> 00:26:53.380
And she wrote everything she
could about the atrocities

00:26:53.380 --> 00:26:56.530
inside the mental hospital.

00:26:56.530 --> 00:26:57.730
Joseph Pulitzer got her out.

00:26:57.730 --> 00:27:01.959
They published a serial story
about all the atrocities

00:27:01.959 --> 00:27:03.500
in the New York
mental health system.

00:27:03.500 --> 00:27:07.510
It led to mental health reform
inside of New York state

00:27:07.510 --> 00:27:09.470
and then eventually
across the country.

00:27:09.470 --> 00:27:12.520
But even more importantly
for Joseph Pulitzer,

00:27:12.520 --> 00:27:15.250
it led to a great
degree of loyalty

00:27:15.250 --> 00:27:16.330
for the "New York World."

00:27:16.330 --> 00:27:18.070
People started subscribing.

00:27:18.070 --> 00:27:19.570
And this teaches
us a lesson, which

00:27:19.570 --> 00:27:22.420
is that where content is
everywhere, as it is today,

00:27:22.420 --> 00:27:25.090
go deep, tell bigger
stories, tell better stories.

00:27:25.090 --> 00:27:27.910
Tell stories that differentiate
you from the next website

00:27:27.910 --> 00:27:28.860
out there.

00:27:28.860 --> 00:27:33.250
That gimmicks are fleeting, but
quality always builds loyalty.

00:27:33.250 --> 00:27:36.020
And again, we see
the flywheel pattern.

00:27:36.020 --> 00:27:37.690
They started
creating content that

00:27:37.690 --> 00:27:39.974
was just sensational headlines.

00:27:39.974 --> 00:27:41.890
They would have the
chain-smoking 11-year-olds

00:27:41.890 --> 00:27:44.410
go and hawk it all over
New York subway stations.

00:27:44.410 --> 00:27:46.660
They'd optimize because
there was no loyalty.

00:27:46.660 --> 00:27:48.850
So then they started
creating better stories,

00:27:48.850 --> 00:27:51.030
deep, investigative stories.

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:54.855
They engaged people, had the
chain-smoking 11-year-olds hawk

00:27:54.855 --> 00:27:56.879
the newspapers all over town.

00:27:56.879 --> 00:27:57.670
And they optimized.

00:27:57.670 --> 00:27:58.545
They got subscribers.

00:27:58.545 --> 00:28:01.030
They got a better
business model.

00:28:01.030 --> 00:28:06.700
And this led to the biggest
newspaper empires and media

00:28:06.700 --> 00:28:08.380
empires in the country.

00:28:08.380 --> 00:28:10.720
Andrew Hearst eventually
adopted this model

00:28:10.720 --> 00:28:13.630
and now has this glimmering
glass tower in New York.

00:28:13.630 --> 00:28:16.630
Joseph Pulitzer took the lessons
that he learned and started

00:28:16.630 --> 00:28:18.960
Columbia Journalism School.

00:28:18.960 --> 00:28:21.280
And this eventually
trickled down

00:28:21.280 --> 00:28:23.200
to all these different trades.

00:28:23.200 --> 00:28:26.590
It wasn't just mass
newspapers that

00:28:26.590 --> 00:28:30.790
were extremely successful,
but verticalized magazines,

00:28:30.790 --> 00:28:34.450
and under Hearst's empire,
in fashion, in news,

00:28:34.450 --> 00:28:37.300
and economics.

00:28:37.300 --> 00:28:39.670
And finally, I want
to show how this has

00:28:39.670 --> 00:28:41.129
applied during the digital age.

00:28:41.129 --> 00:28:42.670
I want to tell the
story of Upworthy.

00:28:42.670 --> 00:28:44.950
I know we often
derive Upworthy today.

00:28:44.950 --> 00:28:47.920
But there's a lot we
can learn from its rise

00:28:47.920 --> 00:28:53.540
into the fastest-growing
media company in history.

00:28:53.540 --> 00:28:58.420
So in 2012, Upworthy
came out, and they

00:28:58.420 --> 00:29:00.370
had a simple idea,
which is that there

00:29:00.370 --> 00:29:03.680
was all this awesome
content that was out there,

00:29:03.680 --> 00:29:06.700
really inspiring
stories on YouTube that

00:29:06.700 --> 00:29:08.350
basically had been thrown away.

00:29:08.350 --> 00:29:12.910
It had really incomprehensible
titles and metadata.

00:29:12.910 --> 00:29:16.150
It wasn't really searchable
or findable by anyone.

00:29:16.150 --> 00:29:18.967
And they thought, what
if we take that garbage--

00:29:18.967 --> 00:29:20.800
it's actually pretty
good-- and repackage it

00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:25.680
in a nice package, different
headlines, very shareable,

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:28.980
very shareable article
format and then

00:29:28.980 --> 00:29:29.980
distribute it out there?

00:29:29.980 --> 00:29:31.390
Test it a bunch
of different ways

00:29:31.390 --> 00:29:34.720
on Facebook, through Facebook
ads, just a few dollars each,

00:29:34.720 --> 00:29:37.840
and figure out which packaging
worked best, which headline,

00:29:37.840 --> 00:29:40.112
which hero images, et cetera.

00:29:40.112 --> 00:29:41.320
And then they would optimize.

00:29:41.320 --> 00:29:43.920
They'd test all these different
ways of getting it out there.

00:29:43.920 --> 00:29:45.072
They'd find the winner.

00:29:45.072 --> 00:29:46.780
And then they'd send
it to as many people

00:29:46.780 --> 00:29:50.521
as possible through organic
and paid Facebook distribution.

00:29:50.521 --> 00:29:53.020
And then, over time, they would
figure out better and better

00:29:53.020 --> 00:29:55.600
ways to package content.

00:29:55.600 --> 00:29:58.540
They'd figure out what types of
videos they could find or make

00:29:58.540 --> 00:30:02.170
worked really well,
really inspired people.

00:30:02.170 --> 00:30:05.830
They'd go and they test it 25
different variations, at least,

00:30:05.830 --> 00:30:07.480
every story.

00:30:07.480 --> 00:30:08.679
And they'd optimize.

00:30:08.679 --> 00:30:10.720
And then they'd figure
out even better packaging,

00:30:10.720 --> 00:30:13.620
the one with the
dinosaurs and the ribbons.

00:30:13.620 --> 00:30:16.020
They'd engage people through
an email newsletter list

00:30:16.020 --> 00:30:17.700
that they built up.

00:30:17.700 --> 00:30:19.020
And they were able to optimize.

00:30:19.020 --> 00:30:21.150
They were able to build
a huge business out of it

00:30:21.150 --> 00:30:24.120
because they got a huge
audience that they built up

00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:26.400
on Facebook and via their
email lists, people who

00:30:26.400 --> 00:30:29.160
loved these inspiring stories.

00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:31.830
And this allowed
Upworthy to become

00:30:31.830 --> 00:30:34.500
the fastest-growing
media company in history,

00:30:34.500 --> 00:30:38.070
to greatly outpace "Business
Insider" and "Huff Post"

00:30:38.070 --> 00:30:41.400
and other fast-growing
media giants of its time.

00:30:41.400 --> 00:30:44.730
Now, eventually, Upworthy
stopped figuring out

00:30:44.730 --> 00:30:46.890
how to optimize
and do things that

00:30:46.890 --> 00:30:49.490
were passed the click-bait
headlines that Facebook cracked

00:30:49.490 --> 00:30:50.400
down on.

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:53.610
But nonetheless,
this cycle worked,

00:30:53.610 --> 00:30:56.590
this pattern worked
extremely well for them.

00:30:56.590 --> 00:30:58.860
And that's because
they were able to crank

00:30:58.860 --> 00:31:01.620
the flywheel faster
than everyone else.

00:31:01.620 --> 00:31:06.150
Other folks out there were
testing different headline

00:31:06.150 --> 00:31:06.660
variations.

00:31:06.660 --> 00:31:09.118
But Upworthy was doing it in
a way where they are committed

00:31:09.118 --> 00:31:13.590
to doing it at rapid speed, to
A/B test as fast as they could,

00:31:13.590 --> 00:31:15.690
and optimize faster
than everyone else.

00:31:15.690 --> 00:31:17.730
And while Upworthy
has faded away--

00:31:17.730 --> 00:31:19.646
I mean, they still have
a pretty good audience

00:31:19.646 --> 00:31:21.600
of 20 million
readers each month--

00:31:21.600 --> 00:31:25.530
we've seen other digital
publishers copy this model.

00:31:25.530 --> 00:31:28.860
And this teaches us that the
faster you crank the flywheel,

00:31:28.860 --> 00:31:30.200
the better it's going to work.

00:31:30.200 --> 00:31:32.610
And as marketers, as
people want to tell stories

00:31:32.610 --> 00:31:36.630
to build audiences, we need to
test and crank that flywheel

00:31:36.630 --> 00:31:37.930
as fast as possible.

00:31:37.930 --> 00:31:39.600
And if we do, we
will get the kind

00:31:39.600 --> 00:31:42.390
of insights that allow
us tell the stories

00:31:42.390 --> 00:31:45.484
that our audience will
really love and engage with.

00:31:45.484 --> 00:31:46.900
And that's why I
believe right now

00:31:46.900 --> 00:31:49.690
we are entering a golden
age for all content types.

00:31:49.690 --> 00:31:52.720
The ability to use technology
to tell incredible stories

00:31:52.720 --> 00:31:54.880
to figure out what
our audience wants,

00:31:54.880 --> 00:31:56.770
to measure the performance
of those stories

00:31:56.770 --> 00:32:01.300
and optimize continuously over
time has never been greater.

00:32:01.300 --> 00:32:05.020
As an individual creator,
you have so many tools

00:32:05.020 --> 00:32:07.720
to go out there and create
incredible interactive data

00:32:07.720 --> 00:32:10.940
visualizations, to create
snowfall style stories,

00:32:10.940 --> 00:32:14.500
to create quick motion
graphic video, even if you're

00:32:14.500 --> 00:32:18.092
someone like me, who isn't a
great coder or a programmer

00:32:18.092 --> 00:32:19.300
or even a great videographer.

00:32:19.300 --> 00:32:22.830
The tools we have out there
are just so tremendous.

00:32:22.830 --> 00:32:27.190
And that the marketer of today
is really today's director.

00:32:27.190 --> 00:32:30.040
But let's not be the
garbage director.

00:32:30.040 --> 00:32:33.050
Let's do content marketing
that breaks through.

00:32:33.050 --> 00:32:35.500
Thank you.

